**************Summary**************

The development of Web 2.0 has resulted in the generation of a vast=20=20
amount of
online discussions. Mining and extracting quality knowledge from online
discussions is significant for the industrial and marketing sector, as=20=
=20
well as
for e-commerce applications. Discussions of this kind encapsulate=20=20
people's
interests and beliefs and hence, there is a great interest in=20=20
acquiring and
developing online discussion analysis tools.
The objective of this thesis is to define a model which represents=20=20
online
discussions and facilitates their analysis. We propose a graph-=20
oriented model.
The vertices of the graph represent postings. Each posting encapsulates
information such as the content of the message, the author who has=20=20
written it,
the opinion polarity of the message and the time that the message was=20=20
posted.
The edges among the postings point out a "reply-to" relation. In other=20=
=20
words
they show which posting replies to what as it is given by the=20=20
structure of the
online discussion.

The proposed model is accompanied by a number of measures which=20=20
facilitate the
discussion mining and the extraction of knowledge from it. Defined=20=20
measures
consist in measures that are underlined by the structure of the=20=20
discussion and
the way the postings are linked to each other. There are opinion-=20
oriented
measures which deal with the opinion evolution within a discussion.
Time-oriented measures exploit the presence of the temporal dimension=20=20
within a
model, while topic-oriented measures can be used in order to measure the
presence of topics within a discussion. The user's presence inside the=20=
=20
online
discussions can be exploited either by social network techniques or=20=20
through the
new model which encapsulates knowledge about the author of each posting.

The representation of an online discussion in the proposed way allows=20=20
a user to
"zoom" inside the discussion. A recommendation of messages is proposed=20=
=20
to the
user to enable a more efficient participation inside the discussion.

Additionally, a prototype system has been implemented which allows the=20=
=20
user to
mine online discussions by selecting a subset of postings and browse=20=20
through
them efficiently.
Keywords: online discussions, opinion mining, text mining, social=20=20
networks,
recommender systems, modeling, forums.

